00:14:40,560 --> 00:14:41,280
In four years.

246
00:14:41,280 --> 00:14:43,280
In four years, it's a shock.

247
00:14:43,280 --> 00:14:45,040
It was what I call a baby shock.

248
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:48,080
And then if you look at Korea, South Korea,

249
00:14:48,080 --> 00:14:50,320
which you mentioned earlier, if we take South Korea,

250
00:14:50,960 --> 00:14:54,080
mid-90s, right in the midst of a currency shock,

251
00:14:54,080 --> 00:14:58,480
you see, childless rates were already maybe 15% there.

252
00:14:58,480 --> 00:15:01,040
Suddenly, it goes up to, I believe, 30%.

253
00:15:01,040 --> 00:15:02,240
And now it's over 40%.

254
00:15:02,240 --> 00:15:03,760
And this is childless at what age?

255
00:15:04,320 --> 00:15:08,400
Well, when I estimate childlessness,

256
00:15:09,040 --> 00:15:13,040
I'm taking, for the given population of women,

257
00:15:13,040 --> 00:15:15,440
the number of births you'd expect to have at any age

258
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:18,000
and saying, how many first-time mothers were there?

259
00:15:18,800 --> 00:15:20,960
And when you count up the number of first-time mothers

260
00:15:20,960 --> 00:15:25,040
of any age group and look at the overall population structure,

261
00:15:25,040 --> 00:15:26,400
you can see, well, wait a minute,

262
00:15:26,400 --> 00:15:30,080
there's a gap opening up here compared to the number you would expect.

263
00:15:30,640 --> 00:15:32,960
So this is like age agnostic, in a sense.

264
00:15:33,920 --> 00:15:36,240
And as a measure, people would say,

265
00:15:36,240 --> 00:15:40,160
well, some of those women might, there might be a boom in the future.

266
00:15:40,160 --> 00:15:42,560
People might be just delaying, but that doesn't happen.

267
00:15:42,640 --> 00:15:44,880
There's no example of those booms ever happening.

268
00:15:46,240 --> 00:15:49,600
So it seems to be we've got this cycle going on

269
00:15:51,200 --> 00:15:54,560
that people are pulled quite quickly into this,

270
00:15:56,880 --> 00:16:00,640
what I call, world of unplanned childlessness, if I can.

271
00:16:00,640 --> 00:16:02,560
I've had to coin quite a few phrases here.

272
00:16:03,520 --> 00:16:07,680
And I should explain what it might mean by unplanned childlessness.

273
00:16:08,640 --> 00:16:13,200
If you look at surveys, look at research,

274
00:16:13,920 --> 00:16:16,720
the vast majority of people want children.

275
00:16:17,280 --> 00:16:17,920
It's innate.

276
00:16:19,360 --> 00:16:21,120
And some don't.

277
00:16:21,120 --> 00:16:22,240
That's clear.

278
00:16:22,240 --> 00:16:24,800
What percentage do approximately?

279
00:16:24,800 --> 00:16:27,040
I'm estimating around 5% don't.

280
00:16:27,040 --> 00:16:29,280
There have been Gallup polls in the U.S. done.

281
00:16:29,280 --> 00:16:30,960
Is that different between men and women?

282
00:16:32,080 --> 00:16:33,120
I don't have that data.

283
00:16:33,120 --> 00:16:33,520
Okay.

284
00:16:33,520 --> 00:16:36,560
So 5% you figure are out of the game?

285
00:16:36,560 --> 00:16:36,800
Yes.

286
00:16:36,800 --> 00:16:38,160
By voluntary choice.

287
00:16:38,160 --> 00:16:38,720
Yes.

288
00:16:38,720 --> 00:16:38,960
Right.

289
00:16:38,960 --> 00:16:41,840
And what percentage are childless?

290
00:16:41,840 --> 00:16:44,400
Well, right now we're looking at 30% to 40%

291
00:16:44,400 --> 00:16:45,440
the most developed nations.

292
00:16:45,440 --> 00:16:49,600
So the vast majority, 80%, it's estimated in studies.

293
00:16:50,320 --> 00:16:51,120
And I think this...

294
00:16:51,120 --> 00:16:54,160
So that's that involuntary childlessness.

295
00:16:54,720 --> 00:16:56,080
And I've been thinking about that lately.

296
00:16:56,080 --> 00:17:01,120
We have this notion for men of involuntary celibacy in cells.

297
00:17:01,120 --> 00:17:06,400
We don't have a term that's at hand for involuntary childlessness

298
00:17:06,480 --> 00:17:07,440
among women.

299
00:17:07,440 --> 00:17:09,200
And it hasn't been recognized as a...

300
00:17:09,920 --> 00:17:11,200
Like what would you call it?

301
00:17:11,200 --> 00:17:14,480
A universal social problem.

302
00:17:14,480 --> 00:17:17,600
But you just said 5% of women don't want children

303
00:17:17,600 --> 00:17:20,080
but 30% don't have them.

304
00:17:20,080 --> 00:17:23,040
And so there's a huge gap there between desire and reality.

305
00:17:23,920 --> 00:17:27,600
So I think frankly, I believe it's the biggest

306
00:17:27,600 --> 00:17:29,920
societal problem that we have.

307
00:17:29,920 --> 00:17:33,200
And it's hiding because we haven't recognized it.

308
00:17:33,200 --> 00:17:36,160
And if you find people, as I did making the documentary,

309
00:17:36,640 --> 00:17:43,840
people who are struggling, 30s, late 30s, women particularly,

310
00:17:43,840 --> 00:17:45,920
but men too, who've given up in their 40s

311
00:17:46,720 --> 00:17:48,240
and they're opening their heart to you

312
00:17:48,240 --> 00:17:50,000
with a level of what they call grief.

313
00:17:51,280 --> 00:17:55,600
And in English language, grief is used for one particular context.

314
00:17:55,600 --> 00:17:59,280
It's not necessarily used normally for something you never had.

315
00:17:59,280 --> 00:18:04,000
I think in other languages, there are terms that encompass that.

316
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:05,200
But it's the same emotion.

317
00:18:05,920 --> 00:18:08,320
And I've been pulled into conversations where

318
00:18:09,040 --> 00:18:14,800
I have frankly been brought myself to the depths of understanding the suffering

319
00:18:14,800 --> 00:18:18,400
from these people who thought they were going through life,

320
00:18:18,400 --> 00:18:22,400
getting the education, starting the career path, probably.

321
00:18:23,280 --> 00:18:25,920
Thinking that, well, you know what, I'm not 30 yet.

322
00:18:26,640 --> 00:18:28,000
I've got time to meet a partner.

323
00:18:29,280 --> 00:18:33,120
And then getting to the point of often, there is no partner.

324
00:18:33,200 --> 00:18:35,520
Or that biology gets in the way.

325
00:18:35,520 --> 00:18:38,160
Yeah, well, it turns out that life is shorter than people think.

326
00:18:39,360 --> 00:18:44,000
I've had clinical clients who followed that path.

327
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:47,360
And some of them were women who had initially decided

328
00:18:47,360 --> 00:18:49,120
that they didn't want to have children

329
00:18:49,120 --> 00:18:52,400
and then changed their minds quite dramatically in their late 20s,

330
00:18:52,400 --> 00:18:56,000
which is a very common pattern, and then couldn't have children.

331
00:18:56,000 --> 00:18:58,320
And it was just absolutely disastrous for them.

332
00:18:58,320 --> 00:19:02,880
They were often on the artificial fertility route for 10 years

333
00:19:02,880 --> 00:19:05,520
with multiple miscarriages and failures on that front.

334
00:19:05,520 --> 00:19:07,280
And it's a bloody dismal outcome.

335
00:19:32,960 --> 00:19:41,840
I think if you caught me at the right day in my 20s,

336
00:19:41,840 --> 00:19:45,920
when I was very in love or excited about a partner,

337
00:19:45,920 --> 00:19:47,040
I would say yes.

338
00:19:48,320 --> 00:19:51,920
But if you were to pry into that, I might say,

339
00:19:51,920 --> 00:19:54,720
I don't know, that seems crazy to have a kid in my 20s.

340
00:20:03,600 --> 00:20:07,520
Okay, so you're making a case here.

341
00:20:08,080 --> 00:20:11,280
You're making a psychological case in some sense at the moment

342
00:20:11,280 --> 00:20:15,120
in that this is a phenomenon worth attending to,

343
00:20:15,120 --> 00:20:19,360
because the vast majority of people who end up childless,

344
00:20:19,360 --> 00:20:22,720
which is a more serious immediate problem for women

345
00:20:22,720 --> 00:20:26,000
because of the biological restrictions on their reproductive capacity.

346
00:20:26,560 --> 00:20:29,040
The reason that's a problem is because so many women

347
00:20:29,920 --> 00:20:32,720
end up in that situation despite wanting children.

348
00:20:32,720 --> 00:20:34,480
So that's a real psychological problem.

349
00:20:34,480 --> 00:20:37,280
But you could take a sociological stance and say,

350
00:20:37,280 --> 00:20:43,120
well, as has been insisted upon for 60 years,

351
00:20:43,120 --> 00:20:44,640
there's too many people on the planet,

352
00:20:44,640 --> 00:20:46,560
and it's just not a bad thing at all

353
00:20:46,560 --> 00:20:48,480
if we stop reproducing in this manner.

354
00:20:48,480 --> 00:20:51,920
And if the price we have to pay for reduction

355
00:20:51,920 --> 00:20:54,560
in the number of excess mouths to feed

356
00:20:54,560 --> 00:20:56,800
is that there are some unhappy women, so be it.

357
00:20:57,360 --> 00:20:58,720
What do you think about this

358
00:20:58,720 --> 00:21:01,280
at a sociological or political or economic level?

359
00:21:01,920 --> 00:21:04,800
Well, first of all, I think that's a terribly sad thing

360
00:21:04,800 --> 00:21:09,920
to contemplate that we have to somehow enforce

361
00:21:11,120 --> 00:21:15,840
perhaps lifelong grief and sadness on a subset of society

362
00:21:15,840 --> 00:21:19,360
who were mostly unlucky enough not to have the children

363
00:21:19,360 --> 00:21:24,400
they wanted to have for the sake of the planet when there are...

364
00:21:24,880 --> 00:21:25,840
Hypothetical, say.

365
00:21:25,840 --> 00:21:29,440
Hypothetical planet at some future time.

366
00:21:29,440 --> 00:21:30,560
At some future time.

367
00:21:31,280 --> 00:21:34,800
And to me, the first thing, my reaction,

368
00:21:34,800 --> 00:21:37,680
strong reaction, isn't there another way, if that's right?

369
00:21:38,240 --> 00:21:42,480
And then you look at data as a reported nature last year

370
00:21:42,480 --> 00:21:45,520
on the overall footprint by age group.

371
00:21:46,800 --> 00:21:48,880
Quite a number of scientists put their name to it,

372
00:21:48,880 --> 00:21:53,200
and it states very clearly that 8% of our footprint

373
00:21:54,080 --> 00:21:56,560
occurs when we're aged under 30.

374
00:21:57,760 --> 00:22:01,360
Then it rises quite significantly between 30 and around 65,

375
00:22:01,360 --> 00:22:03,120
I believe, and then it falls off sharply.

376
00:22:04,480 --> 00:22:09,840
Well, that means that if the world's births were to...

377
00:22:09,840 --> 00:22:11,600
Magically, well, it wouldn't be magic,

378
00:22:11,600 --> 00:22:12,720
dropped by, say, half.

379
00:22:12,720 --> 00:22:14,400
I love taking extreme situations.

380
00:22:14,400 --> 00:22:16,560
So let's imagine that from tomorrow,

381
00:22:16,640 --> 00:22:19,440
only half of the births happen for some crazy reason,

382
00:22:20,240 --> 00:22:24,400
that 8% of total emissions or footprint would go down to 4%

383
00:22:24,960 --> 00:22:26,000
in 30 years' time.

384
00:22:27,040 --> 00:22:30,880
This is going to have almost no impact for decades.

385
00:22:31,520 --> 00:22:34,480
At a time when I think we have to find other solutions

386
00:22:34,480 --> 00:22:37,760
as much as they're needed to solve problems that are out there.

387
00:22:37,760 --> 00:22:40,320
So the idea that we're going to inflict this pain,

388
00:22:41,040 --> 00:22:43,920
deep personal suffering pain in people,

389
00:22:43,920 --> 00:22:47,840
and perhaps be pleased about it, as I know some people are,

390
00:22:49,440 --> 00:22:51,680
I think it's terribly said.

391
00:22:51,680 --> 00:22:54,320
I think it might be that, to come back,

392
00:22:54,320 --> 00:22:56,320
I would like to clarify that for those people

393
00:22:56,320 --> 00:23:01,040
who don't have the desire, I consider myself a pan-natalist.

394
00:23:02,000 --> 00:23:03,280
If you don't want to have children,

395
00:23:03,280 --> 00:23:05,440
I will be your biggest supporter to say that's fine.

396
00:23:06,480 --> 00:23:08,960
And I think there might be a misunderstanding in society

397
00:23:08,960 --> 00:23:11,840
for some people who perhaps don't share that desire,

398
00:23:11,840 --> 00:23:16,080
who perhaps can't quite understand how fundamental this desire is.

399
00:23:16,720 --> 00:23:18,400
Yeah, well, most people who are in that boat

400
00:23:18,400 --> 00:23:21,760
are being willfully blind in my experience.

401
00:23:21,760 --> 00:23:26,960
And so the idea that there are reasons to not want to have children,

402
00:23:26,960 --> 00:23:31,360
one reason is an overwhelming self-centered narcissism.

403
00:23:31,360 --> 00:23:34,800
That's not the only reason, but it's definitely one reason.

404
00:23:34,800 --> 00:23:37,040
And people talk about, you know,

405
00:23:37,040 --> 00:23:39,040
the interference with their personal freedom

406
00:23:39,040 --> 00:23:40,720
and their desire to pursue their career.

407
00:23:40,720 --> 00:23:44,080
And in that, I read something like the absolute inability

408
00:23:44,080 --> 00:23:46,720
to ever sacrifice your own narrow self-interest.

409
00:23:46,720 --> 00:23:51,200
And I do mean narrow to the, what would you say,

410
00:23:51,200 --> 00:23:53,040
concerns and needs of other people.

411
00:23:53,040 --> 00:23:56,560
So, you know, it's interesting to me that it's 5%

412
00:23:57,520 --> 00:23:58,880
that don't want children,

413
00:23:58,880 --> 00:24:02,800
and that the rate of that kind of self-centered narcissism

414
00:24:02,800 --> 00:24:04,400
is about 4-5% too.

415
00:24:04,400 --> 00:24:07,040
Now, I am not saying that everyone who decides

416
00:24:07,040 --> 00:24:09,520
not to have children falls into that category,

417
00:24:09,520 --> 00:24:12,080
but I am saying that a fair number of people

418
00:24:12,080 --> 00:24:14,720
who don't want children fall into that category.

419
00:24:14,720 --> 00:24:17,600
I mean, if you think about it biologically,

420
00:24:17,600 --> 00:24:20,320
every single one of your maternal ancestors

421
00:24:20,320 --> 00:24:23,440
for 3.5 billion years reproduced successfully.

422
00:24:23,440 --> 00:24:26,080
And it might be that you're the exception to that rule.

423
00:24:26,080 --> 00:24:27,520
But, you know, if you are,

424
00:24:27,520 --> 00:24:29,600
you should think long and hard about why.

425
00:24:29,600 --> 00:24:32,800
You also might want to think long and hard about why,

426
00:24:32,800 --> 00:24:36,080
given that it's likely to have a pretty damn detrimental effect

427
00:24:36,080 --> 00:24:37,200
on your life.

428
00:24:37,200 --> 00:24:40,080
You know, it's all fine to be fancy free and footloose

429
00:24:40,080 --> 00:24:41,600
when you're 30 and 35,

430
00:24:41,600 --> 00:24:43,920
but it's a lot less amusing when you're 50,

431
00:24:43,920 --> 00:24:46,640
and it might be downright dreadful by the time you're,

432
00:24:46,640 --> 00:24:47,840
let's say 65.

433
00:24:48,640 --> 00:24:50,320
So, all right.

434
00:24:50,320 --> 00:24:53,760
So, on the population front now,

435
00:24:53,760 --> 00:24:56,480
we talked a little bit about the psychological catastrophe

436
00:24:56,480 --> 00:24:58,160
of involuntary childlessness.

437
00:24:58,720 --> 00:25:03,200
I'm curious too about the social and economic consequences.

438
00:25:03,200 --> 00:25:05,600
So, as you get a demographic bulge,

439
00:25:05,600 --> 00:25:08,400
more and more older people and fewer and fewer younger people,

440
00:25:08,400 --> 00:25:12,640
obviously, you have fewer people to take care of the older people,

441
00:25:12,640 --> 00:25:17,200
but I also have never really read anything pertaining to models

442
00:25:17,200 --> 00:25:20,560
of like real estate value collapse,

443
00:25:20,560 --> 00:25:24,640
because it doesn't take very long if there are more houses

444
00:25:24,640 --> 00:25:29,200
than there are people for the value of real estate to fall to,

445
00:25:29,200 --> 00:25:30,400
well, to what?

446
00:25:30,400 --> 00:25:31,440
To nothing?

447
00:25:31,440 --> 00:25:33,440
I mean, that's what happened in Detroit.

448
00:25:33,440 --> 00:25:35,360
It basically fell to nothing.

449
00:25:35,360 --> 00:25:37,360
I mean, Detroit has recovered to some degree,

450
00:25:37,360 --> 00:25:40,320
but we don't know at all what the world would look like

451
00:25:40,320 --> 00:25:44,000
if real estate values fell to virtually nothing,

452
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:48,640
especially because that's where most people put their retirement value.

453
00:25:48,640 --> 00:25:51,760
So, what do you see, what do you foresee happening

454
00:25:51,760 --> 00:25:54,480
on the political and economic front,

455
00:25:55,360 --> 00:26:00,720
given the shift towards the elderly demographically?

456
00:26:00,720 --> 00:26:03,040
We're going to see it in China first, right, clearly.

457
00:26:03,760 --> 00:26:04,720
Clearly.

458
00:26:04,720 --> 00:26:06,480
Well, Japan too.

459
00:26:06,480 --> 00:26:08,560
One of the reasons I moved to live in Japan

460
00:26:08,560 --> 00:26:10,400
is to be close to...

461
00:26:10,400 --> 00:26:11,840
I wanted to feel this product.

462
00:26:11,840 --> 00:26:14,240
I wanted to be able to see it and almost touch it,

463
00:26:14,240 --> 00:26:15,520
and you can there.

464
00:26:15,520 --> 00:26:17,040
But you mentioned Detroit.

465
00:26:17,040 --> 00:26:20,400
I spent many, many years living in the suburbs of Detroit,

466
00:26:20,960 --> 00:26:24,320
and right around the time I was looking to start this project,

467
00:26:26,480 --> 00:26:28,720
I was able to drive around the streets of Detroit

468
00:26:28,720 --> 00:26:33,360
and see street after street after street of tens and tens of thousands

469
00:26:33,360 --> 00:26:35,920
of decaying houses.

470
00:26:36,880 --> 00:26:40,080
I remember one day driving along and there was a house,

471
00:26:40,640 --> 00:26:45,120
and these were nice houses back in the day, still spacious,

472
00:26:45,920 --> 00:26:49,360
and there was a young family having a picnic outside one of these houses.

473
00:26:50,480 --> 00:26:52,400
And it was the perfect setting, you might say,

474
00:26:52,400 --> 00:26:56,400
and every context except every other house in the street

475
00:26:56,400 --> 00:27:00,160
looked like they were completely vacant, dilapidated.

476
00:27:00,640 --> 00:27:05,840
And around that time, listening to local Detroit news every night,

477
00:27:05,840 --> 00:27:06,960
it was crime.

478
00:27:06,960 --> 00:27:09,280
It was street lights that weren't functioning.

479
00:27:09,280 --> 00:27:10,400
It was lack of safety.

480
00:27:10,400 --> 00:27:12,560
It was lack of functioning of basic utilities.

481
00:27:12,560 --> 00:27:15,680
It was infrastructure and bridges that the city couldn't afford.

482
00:27:15,680 --> 00:27:18,080
And of course, in 2013, it went bankrupt.

483
00:27:18,080 --> 00:27:21,600
So I had this backdrop to knowing what was happening

484
00:27:21,600 --> 00:27:23,840
to Detroit as a city,

485
00:27:23,840 --> 00:27:25,200
and you're running by property value.

486
00:27:25,200 --> 00:27:27,680
Around that time, you could buy a significant property in Detroit

487
00:27:27,680 --> 00:27:28,960
for $10,000.

488
00:27:28,960 --> 00:27:30,640
You probably couldn't go there to ever see it,

489
00:27:30,640 --> 00:27:32,160
because it wasn't safe at that time.

490
00:27:32,160 --> 00:27:32,880
Right, right, right.

491
00:27:32,880 --> 00:27:34,400
And you were right, Detroit has come back.

492
00:27:34,400 --> 00:27:35,520
So in some ways, it is a challenge.

493
00:27:35,520 --> 00:27:37,920
Well, they demolished huge tracts of houses.

494
00:27:37,920 --> 00:27:41,600
But how do you do that when half the houses are still occupied?

495
00:27:41,600 --> 00:27:43,680
You go through this period of time,

496
00:27:43,680 --> 00:27:45,520
unless you're going to say to people,

497
00:27:45,520 --> 00:27:47,680
everybody move three streets over now,

498
00:27:47,680 --> 00:27:49,200
and you do that every few years,

499
00:27:50,000 --> 00:27:52,960
you can't easily go into neighborhoods

500
00:27:52,960 --> 00:27:55,680
and start moving things back to nature,

