1446
01:23:19,280 --> 01:23:21,280
growing population because it's so young,

1447
01:23:21,280 --> 01:23:23,120
people are living longer, which is a good thing.

1448
01:23:23,840 --> 01:23:27,040
But I'm looking at a future for India 30 years from now

1449
01:23:27,040 --> 01:23:29,360
where you're going to have so many old people

1450
01:23:29,920 --> 01:23:31,760
and so few people to take care of them.

1451
01:23:32,960 --> 01:23:37,280
So this is a problem that we focus too much on

1452
01:23:37,280 --> 01:23:38,640
in our own societies.

1453
01:23:39,360 --> 01:23:42,160
This is a global humanitarian crisis of old people

1454
01:23:42,160 --> 01:23:45,760
who are going to be left by and large to some extent

1455
01:23:45,760 --> 01:23:46,800
to fend for themselves.

1456
01:23:46,800 --> 01:23:48,320
And when they're outfending for themselves,

1457
01:23:49,520 --> 01:23:52,080
they're going to be mostly in their homes or alone.

1458
01:23:53,920 --> 01:23:56,400
I find the psychological argument, I would say,

1459
01:23:56,400 --> 01:23:58,240
probably more compelling.

1460
01:23:58,240 --> 01:24:03,280
I think not because I take any issue to your forward-looking projections

1461
01:24:03,280 --> 01:24:06,480
but because things are so unstable

1462
01:24:06,480 --> 01:24:09,360
on the technological and economic and political front

1463
01:24:09,360 --> 01:24:12,640
that projecting even a decade into the future

1464
01:24:12,640 --> 01:24:14,720
seems in some ways like a fool's errand, right?

1465
01:24:14,720 --> 01:24:18,240
Because God only knows what's coming down the pipelines

1466
01:24:18,240 --> 01:24:21,120
with regards to new technology.

1467
01:24:21,120 --> 01:24:23,840
But I think you can make an extraordinarily strong case

1468
01:24:23,840 --> 01:24:27,600
that one of the things you don't want to end up happening

1469
01:24:27,600 --> 01:24:32,080
to you in your own life is to be involuntarily childless

1470
01:24:32,160 --> 01:24:36,720
and isolated starting at the age of 30 going forward, right?

1471
01:24:36,720 --> 01:24:41,760
And so I do, you know, I've looked at the situation in China

1472
01:24:41,760 --> 01:24:44,800
and in Japan with this, what do they call that,

1473
01:24:44,800 --> 01:24:47,200
the inverted pyramidal distribution

1474
01:24:47,200 --> 01:24:49,440
where there's way more old people than young people.

1475
01:24:49,440 --> 01:24:52,320
And obviously that seems untenable on the technological

1476
01:24:52,320 --> 01:24:53,680
or on the economic front.

1477
01:24:54,240 --> 01:25:01,760
But I do think the psychological issue is much more present,

1478
01:25:01,760 --> 01:25:03,600
should be much more present for young people.

1479
01:25:03,600 --> 01:25:06,160
And the warning is don't be thinking you've got a lot of time

1480
01:25:06,160 --> 01:25:07,040
to get your act together

1481
01:25:07,040 --> 01:25:09,200
because you don't have as much time as you think

1482
01:25:09,200 --> 01:25:12,400
and you want to get things going sooner than you

1483
01:25:13,360 --> 01:25:14,960
might find it convenient.

1484
01:25:14,960 --> 01:25:16,640
There's never a convenient time to have a child.

1485
01:25:17,280 --> 01:25:19,600
There's stupid times to have a child for sure,

1486
01:25:19,600 --> 01:25:21,040
but there's never a convenient time.

1487
01:25:21,040 --> 01:25:22,800
And that's the other thing people do too, you know.

1488
01:25:24,080 --> 01:25:26,320
When my wife and I finally got together,

1489
01:25:26,320 --> 01:25:27,520
she was about 28 or so,

1490
01:25:27,520 --> 01:25:30,960
she wanted to have a kid pretty, you know, pretty much right away.

1491
01:25:31,600 --> 01:25:34,560
And I was finishing off my post-doc

1492
01:25:34,560 --> 01:25:36,320
and I hadn't got a permanent job yet.

1493
01:25:36,320 --> 01:25:40,080
And my sense was, well, you know, everything's not in place.

1494
01:25:40,080 --> 01:25:42,000
And we talked that out for quite a while

1495
01:25:42,000 --> 01:25:44,080
and decided to proceed regardless

1496
01:25:44,080 --> 01:25:48,400
because there was no real reason for me to be concerned.

1497
01:25:48,400 --> 01:25:50,400
The probability that I was going to be jobless

1498
01:25:50,400 --> 01:25:53,360
was barring catastrophes zero.

1499
01:25:53,360 --> 01:25:57,840
And you jump into the abyss holding hands with your wife,

1500
01:25:57,840 --> 01:25:59,760
you know, there's no right time.

1501
01:26:00,640 --> 01:26:02,800
And the reason that's so important to know

1502
01:26:02,800 --> 01:26:05,440
is because the clock ticks while you're waiting,

1503
01:26:05,440 --> 01:26:07,280
and that's also a catastrophe.

1504
01:26:07,280 --> 01:26:10,640
And then it sneaks up on people unaware as you just described

1505
01:26:10,640 --> 01:26:12,560
and takes them out, not good.

1506
01:26:13,120 --> 01:26:14,480
Okay, so now you're talking,

1507
01:26:14,480 --> 01:26:16,320
now you're investigating in the documentary

1508
01:26:16,320 --> 01:26:19,280
the consequences of this involuntary childlessness

1509
01:26:19,280 --> 01:26:21,840
and do you progress past that?

1510
01:26:21,840 --> 01:26:25,520
Yeah, well, so the consequences go into both the economic,

1511
01:26:25,520 --> 01:26:26,880
we go to Detroit,

1512
01:26:26,880 --> 01:26:29,040
we look at what might happen to the future

1513
01:26:29,040 --> 01:26:30,960
of the world based on what's happened to Detroit.

1514
01:26:30,960 --> 01:26:31,200
Yeah.

1515
01:26:31,920 --> 01:26:37,040
Yeah, we look at briefly future pension systems,

1516
01:26:37,040 --> 01:26:40,800
we look at AI technology, but only very briefly.

1517
01:26:40,800 --> 01:26:42,400
It's an area that I'm sure many people

1518
01:26:42,400 --> 01:26:44,320
like you mentioned technology just now,

1519
01:26:44,320 --> 01:26:49,040
but a comment for me is that robots don't pay taxes.

1520
01:26:49,040 --> 01:26:50,080
So simply saying this will be-

1521
01:26:50,080 --> 01:26:52,480
They also don't necessarily want to take care of you.

1522
01:26:53,360 --> 01:26:55,040
So we'll just see how that works out.

1523
01:26:55,600 --> 01:26:57,040
And I think they're going to be expensive.

1524
01:26:57,040 --> 01:27:00,080
So the idea that AI is a solution just like this

1525
01:27:00,880 --> 01:27:05,280
is probably oversimplified, possibly very oversimplified,

1526
01:27:05,280 --> 01:27:06,320
but of course it has a role,

1527
01:27:06,320 --> 01:27:08,560
technology definitely has a role in this.

1528
01:27:08,560 --> 01:27:10,320
But we can't just turn away from this subject

1529
01:27:10,320 --> 01:27:12,480
and say, let's not worry about it for that reason.

1530
01:27:13,280 --> 01:27:14,800
The final part of the documentary,

1531
01:27:14,800 --> 01:27:16,960
and I have to credit a friend,

1532
01:27:16,960 --> 01:27:20,080
I thought it was done after filming in probably teen countries.

1533
01:27:20,080 --> 01:27:21,440
I thought, well, this is enough now,

1534
01:27:21,440 --> 01:27:23,440
kind of I can see the global pattern.

1535
01:27:24,320 --> 01:27:27,360
And this friend in LA said, no, you haven't finished,

1536
01:27:27,360 --> 01:27:28,720
you have to go to Africa.

1537
01:27:28,720 --> 01:27:30,880
And you have to go to other countries like Bangladesh.

1538
01:27:32,480 --> 01:27:33,600
And India had already been to,

1539
01:27:33,600 --> 01:27:34,880
but I wanted to more filming.

1540
01:27:34,880 --> 01:27:35,760
I wanted to go into-

1541
01:27:35,760 --> 01:27:37,760
We went to slums in Mumbai.

1542
01:27:37,760 --> 01:27:43,120
We went to slums in Rio, I think five in Johannesburg.

