1553
01:28:17,520 --> 01:28:19,360
Yeah, and you look at Nigeria,

1554
01:28:19,360 --> 01:28:21,760
you look at Nigeria and you still have a culture there

1555
01:28:21,760 --> 01:28:24,240
where the more male children you have,

1556
01:28:24,240 --> 01:28:27,440
it's part of what you might say, the bravado that you have.

1557
01:28:27,440 --> 01:28:30,320
Yeah, yeah, that's that status reward status.

1558
01:28:30,320 --> 01:28:32,880
But you go to Ethiopia and you meet people there

1559
01:28:32,880 --> 01:28:34,080
and you talk to professors there.

1560
01:28:34,080 --> 01:28:35,680
And Ethiopia used to be like that,

1561
01:28:35,680 --> 01:28:37,920
but the birth rate right now in Ethiopia is four.

1562
01:28:37,920 --> 01:28:40,000
It used to be seven or eight, not that long ago,

1563
01:28:40,000 --> 01:28:42,480
and there's a transformation happening.

1564
01:28:42,480 --> 01:28:46,160
So you can see and feel the transformation happening in Africa,

1565
01:28:46,160 --> 01:28:47,360
just like everywhere else.

1566
01:28:47,360 --> 01:28:48,960
So I like to think of the analogy

1567
01:28:48,960 --> 01:28:50,880
that the world is on a rollercoaster

1568
01:28:52,160 --> 01:28:55,040
and countries like Japan and Germany and Italy

1569
01:28:55,040 --> 01:28:57,760
and now South Korea are in the front car.

1570
01:28:57,760 --> 01:29:00,240
They're over in terms of the peak population

1571
01:29:00,880 --> 01:29:03,200
and sure they're aging and people are going to live longer

1572
01:29:03,200 --> 01:29:05,280
and longer, so we're not going to really see

1573
01:29:05,280 --> 01:29:08,640
the drop for a little while, but we know what's coming.

1574
01:29:09,200 --> 01:29:11,360
Africa is in the rear car.

1575
01:29:11,360 --> 01:29:14,480
They're still on the way up, but the path is the same here.

1576
01:29:14,480 --> 01:29:19,200
Yeah, but perhaps the thing that struck me about Africa,

1577
01:29:19,200 --> 01:29:22,240
where I'm planning to go back and spend a significant amount of time

1578
01:29:22,240 --> 01:29:25,440
for my own purposes as much as anything,

1579
01:29:25,440 --> 01:29:28,240
when you go to Africa, you go to Malawi,

1580
01:29:28,240 --> 01:29:30,320
which is, I believe, World Bank data,

1581
01:29:30,320 --> 01:29:34,000
the 12th poorest country in the world by GDP per person.

1582
01:29:35,680 --> 01:29:39,440
And you go to a community and people are laughing, smiling.

1583
01:29:40,000 --> 01:29:43,520
And you go to kind of an area, it's not even a soccer pitch,

1584
01:29:43,520 --> 01:29:46,000
it's nothing like a soccer pitch, but there's a soccer ball there.

1585
01:29:46,000 --> 01:29:49,920
There's no rules, but you've got 30 kids running and screaming and laughing.

1586
01:29:49,920 --> 01:29:53,040
And we're there, and they come and say hi for a moment,

1587
01:29:53,040 --> 01:29:55,040
but they want to get back and play soccer with each other.

1588
01:29:55,840 --> 01:29:58,320
And to see that sense of community

1589
01:29:59,040 --> 01:30:01,360
and that intergenerational community,

1590
01:30:02,240 --> 01:30:05,360
maybe in some ways part of a solution here that we've,

1591
01:30:05,360 --> 01:30:08,240
I think an argument for me is that we've lost a sense of community

1592
01:30:08,240 --> 01:30:09,440
for one reason or another.

1593
01:30:10,400 --> 01:30:18,720
And so that's something that surprised me, actually, how similar, really,

1594
01:30:18,720 --> 01:30:23,600
we all are, and we're just different parts of that cycle.

1595
01:30:25,600 --> 01:30:28,800
So you've laid out this documentary,

1596
01:30:28,800 --> 01:30:34,000
and you've documented a problem that is not being attended to much.

1597
01:30:34,880 --> 01:30:36,960
That's a very pervasive problem,

1598
01:30:36,960 --> 01:30:42,720
and that's going to affect virtually everyone personally and sociologically.

1599
01:30:43,360 --> 01:30:46,080
We talked a little bit about pathways.

1600
01:30:47,760 --> 01:30:49,920
It's one thing, obviously, to diagnose a problem,

1601
01:30:49,920 --> 01:30:52,000
and that's not a straightforward thing to do,

1602
01:30:52,000 --> 01:30:53,840
to see the problem and then to diagnose it.

1603
01:30:54,560 --> 01:30:58,160
It's a completely different order of things to start thinking about

1604
01:30:58,160 --> 01:31:00,560
what might constitute an acceptable alternative.

1605
01:31:00,560 --> 01:31:03,200
So in Hungary, what they've done, you probably know this,

1606
01:31:03,200 --> 01:31:07,680
is that if you're a mother in Hungary and you have one child,

1607
01:31:08,560 --> 01:31:12,320
you're now exempt from income tax at the federal level for the rest of your life,

1608
01:31:12,320 --> 01:31:17,200
25%, and then that scales up to 100% for four children.

1609
01:31:17,200 --> 01:31:20,240
And the idea there was both practical and cultural.

1610
01:31:20,240 --> 01:31:25,840
So the cultural idea was we need to signal that we value motherhood and children.

1611
01:31:26,400 --> 01:31:32,880
And one of the more powerful signals that society has access to

1612
01:31:32,880 --> 01:31:33,920
is economic signals.

1613
01:31:33,920 --> 01:31:38,160
And the Hungarians have stopped the decline in their birth rate and tapped it up slightly.

1614
01:31:38,160 --> 01:31:41,920
They've increased female participation in the workforce, by the way, 13%.

1615
01:31:42,960 --> 01:31:45,120
So the feminists had objected, or some of them,

1616
01:31:45,120 --> 01:31:49,360
that the Hungarian government was just turning women into baby-making factories,

1617
01:31:49,360 --> 01:31:54,080
which is hell of a nasty epithet, I might add.

1618
01:31:54,080 --> 01:31:56,480
But what's happened is the reverse.

1619
01:31:56,480 --> 01:31:58,400
As more women are working now than before,

1620
01:31:58,400 --> 01:32:00,640
and I suppose that's because they get to keep more of their money,

1621
01:32:01,600 --> 01:32:05,520
and they can make childcare arrangements more straightforwardly and all of that,

1622
01:32:05,520 --> 01:32:08,560
they've knocked a divorce rate down substantively.

1623
01:32:08,560 --> 01:32:10,160
They've increased the marriage rate.

1624
01:32:10,160 --> 01:32:15,040
They've knocked the abortion rate down 40%, 38%, with no compulsion.

1625
01:32:15,040 --> 01:32:19,520
It's not as easy to get an abortion in Hungary as it is in the US or Canada.

1626
01:32:20,160 --> 01:32:25,520
And the legal limits there is 12 weeks instead of the 16 weeks,

1627
01:32:25,520 --> 01:32:28,080
which is about what Americans think it should be.

1628
01:32:28,080 --> 01:32:36,320
But the point is these alterations in policy have produced increases in fertility,

1629
01:32:36,320 --> 01:32:39,200
increases in the marital rate, decreases in the divorce rate,

1630
01:32:39,200 --> 01:32:43,360
decreases in the abortion rate, and those look arguably like desirable things.

1631
01:32:45,120 --> 01:32:48,560
And we talked a little bit about the fact that women live seven years longer,

1632
01:32:48,560 --> 01:32:52,720
and so in principle, have a time, let's say eight years,

1633
01:32:52,720 --> 01:32:56,880
where they could have children without really being at a competitive disadvantage

1634
01:32:56,880 --> 01:33:01,040
on the economic front with men, assuming that it is a competitive landscape,

1635
01:33:01,040 --> 01:33:03,200
and that's also not particularly obvious to me.

1636
01:33:03,840 --> 01:33:11,600
I mean, have your thoughts turned to what might constitute an appropriate pathway forward

1637
01:33:11,600 --> 01:33:12,800
for young people?

1638
01:33:12,800 --> 01:33:20,000
Well, I certainly would quite boldly say what will not work,

1639
01:33:20,000 --> 01:33:23,600
because there's so many examples of things that have been tried and tried and tried and tried.

1640
01:33:23,600 --> 01:33:26,000
Now, we'll come back to Hungary in a moment, because it is very interesting.

1641
01:33:27,600 --> 01:33:31,680
But if you look at baby bonus programs globally,

1642
01:33:31,680 --> 01:33:35,840
at best, what they do is temporarily increase the birth rate,

1643
01:33:37,040 --> 01:33:40,560
and then you see a dip, and the dip usually goes below where it was before.

1644
01:33:40,560 --> 01:33:46,160
All you've done is bring forward the people who would have had kids anyway.

1645
01:33:46,160 --> 01:33:47,600
Yeah, yeah, right, right.

1646
01:33:48,240 --> 01:33:51,440
So we, and you look at the amount of money in certain Japan,

1647
01:33:51,440 --> 01:33:54,240
certainly South Korea are spending on kindergarten.

1648
01:33:54,240 --> 01:33:55,680
Yeah, yeah, that doesn't seem to help.

1649
01:33:55,680 --> 01:33:57,200
Quebec, it didn't make a bit of difference.

1650
01:33:57,200 --> 01:33:57,760
Yeah, yeah.

1651
01:33:57,760 --> 01:33:58,480
No, it isn't.

1652
01:33:58,480 --> 01:34:01,040
It isn't lack of childcare that's causing this problem.

1653
01:34:01,040 --> 01:34:02,720
Yeah, and it's not income either.

1654
01:34:02,720 --> 01:34:03,840
No, right.

1655
01:34:03,840 --> 01:34:05,360
A lot of people think it is income.

1656
01:34:05,360 --> 01:34:07,440
It's a natural thing, I think, for people thinking,

1657
01:34:07,440 --> 01:34:10,000
well, if I had a little bit more money at the right time,

1658
01:34:10,560 --> 01:34:12,240
or my apartment's too small,

1659
01:34:12,240 --> 01:34:16,400
but actually what you find is that when people have more money in their pocket,

1660
01:34:16,400 --> 01:34:17,440
birth rates go down.

1661
01:34:17,440 --> 01:34:17,600
Yeah, right.

1662
01:34:17,600 --> 01:34:18,400
They do other things.

1663
01:34:18,400 --> 01:34:18,800
Yeah, yeah.

1664
01:34:18,800 --> 01:34:20,960
It's like, not yet, we can take this vacation.

1665
01:34:20,960 --> 01:34:22,000
Well, I think also,

1666
01:34:22,080 --> 01:34:26,080
well, I also think that their expectations for what constitutes

1667
01:34:26,080 --> 01:34:28,720
sufficiently prepared for children also change.

1668
01:34:29,840 --> 01:34:31,440
Like I said, when I was in Montreal,

1669
01:34:31,440 --> 01:34:33,040
well, I was already educated.

1670
01:34:33,040 --> 01:34:33,840
I had a job.

1671
01:34:33,840 --> 01:34:35,360
It was clear I was going to get a job,

1672
01:34:35,360 --> 01:34:38,800
but my standard for what was sufficient security

1673
01:34:38,800 --> 01:34:40,320
and opportunity for my children

1674
01:34:40,320 --> 01:34:43,920
rose along with my horizon of vision on the economic front.

1675
01:34:43,920 --> 01:34:47,280
And it's also not the case that more security makes you

1676
01:34:48,080 --> 01:34:49,920
likeable to take more risks.

1677
01:34:49,920 --> 01:34:51,200
That isn't how life works.

1678
01:34:51,200 --> 01:34:52,640
You have to jump into children,

1679
01:34:52,640 --> 01:34:54,880
just like you jump into a marriage

1680
01:34:54,880 --> 01:34:57,360
or into your life for that matter.

1681
01:34:57,360 --> 01:34:58,640
I think that's the key point.

1682
01:34:58,640 --> 01:35:01,920
So ultimately, Hungary aside for a moment,

1683
01:35:01,920 --> 01:35:03,280
and also Russia in the past,

1684
01:35:03,280 --> 01:35:04,880
has had similar programs

1685
01:35:04,880 --> 01:35:07,680
where they have put significant benefits in place

1686
01:35:07,680 --> 01:35:09,440
that seem to work for a time.

1687
01:35:10,640 --> 01:35:14,880
But vast majority of financial incentives

1688
01:35:14,880 --> 01:35:17,920
or even societal changes

